{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.65,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81324"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28547"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81324"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is admitted to the rehabilitation ward following a motor vehicle accident two weeks ago. He sustained a severe traumatic brain injury and was initially managed in the intensive care unit. He is now following commands and engaging in basic conversation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he correctly states his name but is uncertain of the date and his location. He scores 9/12 on the Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale, answering questions about orientation correctly but failing the memory component.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate frequency for ongoing post-traumatic amnesia testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Daily until one perfect score","Weekly until discharge","Daily until three consecutive perfect scores","Twice daily until perfect score","Three times per week until discharge"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-traumatic amnesia (PTA) is a state of confusion and disorientation that occurs following traumatic brain injury. The duration of PTA is one of the most reliable predictors of functional outcome following traumatic brain injury, making accurate assessment crucial for prognostication and rehabilitation planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily until three consecutive perfect scores\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct testing frequency. This approach ensures that the patient has genuinely emerged from PTA rather than having a single good day. The Westmead PTA Scale requires a score of 12/12 on three consecutive days to confirm emergence from PTA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeekly until discharge\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for monitoring PTA emergence. This infrequent testing could miss the actual time of emergence and lead to inaccurate prognostication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwice daily until perfect score\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily frequent and may be distressing for the patient. Additionally, a single perfect score is insufficient to confirm PTA emergence unless 28 days have passed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily until one perfect score\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient to confirm true emergence from PTA, as cognitive function can fluctuate during recovery. However, once the patient has received 28 days of continuous PTA testing they will no longer be required to achieve 3 consecutive days of perfect scores, they will only need one day of 12/12 score\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree times per week until discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate monitoring of PTA emergence and could delay recognition of cognitive improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Westmead PTA Scale assesses orientation (time, place, person) and memory (ability to recall pictures shown in previous testing). It is specifically designed for use in traumatic brain injury and has been validated in Australian populations. The duration of PTA is measured from the time of injury until the first day of three consecutive perfect scores.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-traumatic amnesia testing should continue daily until the patient achieves a perfect score on three consecutive days.","The Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale assesses orientation and memory in traumatic brain injury.","Accurate PTA duration assessment is crucial for prognostication in traumatic brain injury."],"references":["St George/Sutherland Hospitals And Health Services (SGSHHS), POST TRAUMATIC AMNESIA (PTA) TESTING - PROTOCOL FOR, 2015, https://www.seslhd.health.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/groups/StGTrauma/Policies/SGSHHS_CLIN155_Post_Trauma_Amnesia_testing.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T20:47:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-21T21:55:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81324"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/